1
00:01:04,650 --> 00:01:08,484
Typical of Victor Von Doom to build
a 30-foot statue of himself.

2
00:01:08,738 --> 00:01:11,127
Well, it's obviously aimed
at first-time visitors...

3
00:01:11,324 --> 00:01:14,521
to create feelings
of smallness, inadequacy.

4
00:01:15,995 --> 00:01:17,747
Good thing it ain't working.

5
00:01:18,498 --> 00:01:22,252
Reed, what are we doing here?
This guy's fast-food, strip-mall science.

6
00:01:22,543 --> 00:01:24,693
This wasn't our first stop,
in case you forgot.

7
00:01:24,879 --> 00:01:28,997
Besides, Victor's not that bad.
He's just a little larger than life.

8
00:01:37,558 --> 00:01:41,517
My research suggests that exposure
to a high-energy cosmic storm...

9
00:01:41,771 --> 00:01:46,162
borne on solar winds might have triggered
the evolution of early planetary life.

10
00:01:47,151 --> 00:01:51,667
In six weeks, another cloud
with the same elemental profile...

11
00:01:51,948 --> 00:01:53,666
will pass Earth's orbit.

12
00:01:54,742 --> 00:01:58,530
A study conducted in space could
fundamentally advance our knowledge...

13
00:01:58,788 --> 00:02:01,985
about the structure of the human genome,
cure countless diseases...

14
00:02:02,208 --> 00:02:06,281
extend human life, give kids a chance
to live longer, stronger, healthier...

15
00:02:06,546 --> 00:02:08,537
Turn it off, please.

16
00:02:08,923 --> 00:02:10,993
I don't think I have explained
my proposal fully.

17
00:02:11,175 --> 00:02:12,847
No, I think you have.

18
00:02:13,052 --> 00:02:15,520
Same old Reed, always stretching,
reaching for the stars...

19
00:02:15,722 --> 00:02:18,077
with the weight of the world on his back.

20
00:02:18,266 --> 00:02:20,336
But dreams don't pay the bills, do they?

21
00:02:22,603 --> 00:02:26,516
You remember, when we were in school
we talked about working together.

22
00:02:26,774 --> 00:02:29,129
Well, that's what I was about to explain.

23
00:02:30,737 --> 00:02:31,931
The storm is deadly.

24
00:02:32,071 --> 00:02:34,027
But the shields on
your station's control room...

25
00:02:34,198 --> 00:02:36,666
are designed to protect
any occupants inside.

26
00:02:39,787 --> 00:02:42,017
So it's not just my money you want.

27
00:02:42,665 --> 00:02:43,814
It's my toys.

28
00:02:45,293 --> 00:02:48,205
Tell me, if NASA doesn't trust you,
then why should I?

29
00:02:52,091 --> 00:02:54,685
That's my job, to stay a step ahead.

30
00:02:55,386 --> 00:02:58,617
To know what other men don't.

31
00:02:58,848 --> 00:03:00,247
I can't take this.

32
00:03:00,391 --> 00:03:02,382
Ben, this is business, just work.

33
00:03:02,560 --> 00:03:04,949
He's right, Ben. It is just business.

34
00:03:06,189 --> 00:03:10,068
I think you both know my Director
of Genetic Research, Susan Storm.

35
00:03:14,155 --> 00:03:15,747
One more thing he's got.

36
00:03:16,324 --> 00:03:18,201
- Hey, Susie.
- Hey.

37
00:03:18,534 --> 00:03:21,651
It's so nice to see you. How's Debbie?

38
00:03:21,871 --> 00:03:23,270
- Great.
- Great.

39
00:03:25,792 --> 00:03:27,862
- How have you been?
- Never better.

40
00:03:30,463 --> 00:03:32,374
This isn't going to be a problem, is it?

41
00:03:32,548 --> 00:03:33,742
- No.
- Not at all.

42
00:03:33,883 --> 00:03:35,032
Good.

43
00:03:35,468 --> 00:03:39,143
Then you're just in time
to hear the great Reed Richards...

44
00:03:39,389 --> 00:03:41,584
ask me for help.

45
00:03:42,475 --> 00:03:46,263
You know, you made a lot of folks at MIT
feel like a junior high science fair.

46
00:03:46,521 --> 00:03:49,115
So you'll excuse me
if I savor the moment.

47
00:03:50,817 --> 00:03:54,332
You back this mission and I'll sign over
a fair percentage of any application...

48
00:03:54,570 --> 00:03:55,844
The number's 75%.

49
00:03:56,322 --> 00:03:57,914
And its applications and patents.

50
00:03:58,074 --> 00:04:00,110
- What about his first-born?
- Ben...

51
00:04:00,952 --> 00:04:02,146
Come on.

52
00:04:02,662 --> 00:04:06,371
25% of a billion is enough
to keep the lights on for a while, isn't it?

53
00:04:06,958 --> 00:04:10,268
Maybe even pay off your fourth mortgage
on the Baxter Building.

54
00:04:11,671 --> 00:04:12,740
Deal?

55
00:04:21,556 --> 00:04:24,070
Well, then. To our future.

56
00:04:26,686 --> 00:04:27,914
Together!

57
00:04:29,939 --> 00:04:32,248
It's funny how things turn out, isn't it?

58
00:04:33,359 --> 00:04:34,508
Hilarious.

59
00:04:37,530 --> 00:04:40,806
He knew about NASA.
Maybe he made the call to shut us down.

60
00:04:41,034 --> 00:04:44,231
Ben, think about all the people
we can help if this works.

61
00:04:44,704 --> 00:04:47,059
Look, we got what we wanted.
That's enough.

62
00:04:47,248 --> 00:04:50,046
A few days in space, it'll be great.
What's the worst that can happen?

63
00:04:55,173 --> 00:04:58,529
If Reed's right, this little trip
could double our stock offerings.

64
00:04:58,760 --> 00:05:00,990
- And if he's not...
- Reed's always right.

65
00:05:01,929 --> 00:05:04,568
Good thing he doesn't always know
what he's got.

66
00:05:14,150 --> 00:05:16,789
Reed, you should know those solar winds
have been picking up speed.

67
00:05:16,986 --> 00:05:18,624
I factored them into my coordinates.

68
00:05:18,780 --> 00:05:21,089
Right, of course you did. In theory.

69
00:05:21,282 --> 00:05:23,113
It's a little different once you're out there.

70
00:05:23,284 --> 00:05:25,434
- I can assure you I...
- When are we leaving?

71
00:05:27,580 --> 00:05:28,979
I'll be scheduling the launch...

72
00:05:29,123 --> 00:05:32,115
so you can call me in the morning
for resources and crew.

73
00:05:32,877 --> 00:05:35,596
- I think I remember the number.
- It's been changed.

74
00:05:42,178 --> 00:05:45,170
As far as crew, I was hoping
Ben could pilot the mission.

75
00:05:45,390 --> 00:05:48,780
We already have a pilot on our payroll,
but you're welcome to ride shotgun.

76
00:05:49,018 --> 00:05:50,736
Remember my brother, Johnny?

77
00:06:07,912 --> 00:06:10,187
Can't do it. Cannot do it.

78
00:06:10,373 --> 00:06:14,048
External SRBs, orbital system engines,
it's just like the shuttle you flew.

79
00:06:14,293 --> 00:06:17,171
No! I cannot take orders
from the underwear model.

80
00:06:17,380 --> 00:06:19,655
- Come on now, Ben.
- That wingnut washed out of NASA...

81
00:06:19,841 --> 00:06:23,356
for sneaking two Victoria's Secret
wannabes into a flight simulator.

82
00:06:23,594 --> 00:06:25,027
Youthful high spirits.

83
00:06:25,179 --> 00:06:28,808
They crashed it into a wall.
A flight simulator.

84
00:06:29,392 --> 00:06:31,110
When have I ever asked you
to do something...

85
00:06:31,269 --> 00:06:32,827
you absolutely said you could not do?

86
00:06:32,979 --> 00:06:34,048
Five times.

87
00:06:34,981 --> 00:06:37,290
- I had it at four.
- Well, this makes five.

88
00:06:47,577 --> 00:06:49,135
<i>Attention, all personnel. </i>

89
00:06:49,287 --> 00:06:52,279
<i>Commencing launch sequence</i>
<i>in six hours. </i>

90
00:06:52,498 --> 00:06:54,250
I miss you already, Debs.

91
00:06:54,417 --> 00:06:56,055
Captain on the bridge!

92
00:06:58,629 --> 00:07:02,588
Digital camera: $254. Memory stick: $59.

93
00:07:03,092 --> 00:07:05,970
The look on your hard-ass
former CO's face...

94
00:07:06,179 --> 00:07:08,568
when he finds out he's your junior officer:

95
00:07:09,182 --> 00:07:10,331
Priceless.

96
00:07:13,311 --> 00:07:14,630
Thank you. That's so sweet.

97
00:07:14,771 --> 00:07:16,489
I can handle the ship.

98
00:07:16,647 --> 00:07:18,877
I can even handle Mr. Blond Ambition.

99
00:07:19,067 --> 00:07:22,423
But I don't know whether I should be
flying or doing Swan Lake in these suits.

100
00:07:22,653 --> 00:07:25,565
- I mean, who the hell came up with these?
- Victor did.

101
00:07:25,782 --> 00:07:29,980
The synthetics act as a second skin,
adapting to your body's individual needs.

102
00:07:30,703 --> 00:07:33,092
See, now that means
it keeps the hot stuff hot...

103
00:07:33,289 --> 00:07:35,280
and it keeps the cool stuff cool.

104
00:07:35,917 --> 00:07:38,033
Wow. Fantastic.

105
00:07:38,753 --> 00:07:41,665
Material made from self-regulating
unstable molecules.

106
00:07:42,924 --> 00:07:45,199
I've been working on a formula for this.

107
00:07:46,260 --> 00:07:48,012
Great minds think alike.

108
00:07:50,973 --> 00:07:53,533
- Here you go, Ben.
- Thanks, sweetie.

109
00:07:53,726 --> 00:07:54,841
Reed.

110
00:08:27,844 --> 00:08:30,074
ETA until cosmic event: Nine hours.

111
00:08:30,638 --> 00:08:33,311
If you're good, maybe next time
Daddy'll let you drive.

112
00:08:33,516 --> 00:08:36,155
You keep talking
and there won't be a next time.

113
00:08:39,355 --> 00:08:43,064
Long way from the projection booth
at the Hayden Planetarium, isn't it?

114
00:08:47,655 --> 00:08:49,850
Yes. Yes, it is.

115
00:08:51,534 --> 00:08:55,083
We can monitor the cloud's approach
and observe the tests from here.

116
00:08:56,205 --> 00:08:57,274
Is it safe?

117
00:08:57,790 --> 00:09:00,350
The shields on the station
should protect us.

118
00:09:00,793 --> 00:09:01,908
Should?

119
00:09:02,045 --> 00:09:05,401
What's the matter, Ben?
Getting paranoid in your old age?

120
00:09:06,215 --> 00:09:09,810
Let's start loading those samples.
Get your suit ready, Ben.

121
00:09:11,429 --> 00:09:14,182
So I see you're still doing
all the heavy lifting.

122
00:09:14,807 --> 00:09:18,595
Maybe you should have stayed in the lab.
Fieldwork never suited you.

123
00:09:18,853 --> 00:09:22,129
He does the talking, I do the walking.
Got it?

124
00:09:23,441 --> 00:09:24,920
So take a walk, Ben.

125
00:09:25,610 --> 00:09:29,967
Actually, if you'll all excuse me,
I need to borrow Susan for a moment.

126
00:09:34,702 --> 00:09:35,771
Sure.

127
00:09:38,956 --> 00:09:42,073
Please tell me your guy's not trying
to rekindle things with my sister again.

128
00:09:42,293 --> 00:09:44,523
Of course not. It's strictly business.

129
00:09:44,712 --> 00:09:47,431
Yes, well, his eyes say differently,
don't they?

130
00:09:48,925 --> 00:09:52,713
Two hearts got busted last time.
Maybe she's not over it, either.

131
00:09:53,012 --> 00:09:56,288
Wow, Dr. Phil, that's deep.
Let's think about that.

132
00:09:56,766 --> 00:10:00,042
You got Victor, more money than God,
stud of the year.

133
00:10:01,020 --> 00:10:05,411
And you got Reed, world's dumbest smart
guy, worth less than a postage stamp.

134
00:10:06,484 --> 00:10:07,678
That's a real toss-up.

135
00:10:07,819 --> 00:10:09,889
Don't trouble your tiny little mind.

136
00:10:10,488 --> 00:10:12,160
Don't wander off now, boy.

137
00:10:14,701 --> 00:10:16,612
<i>Securing airlock chamber. </i>

138
00:10:36,347 --> 00:10:38,542
Surprised I agreed to Reed's proposal?

139
00:10:38,725 --> 00:10:40,716
I understand the business reasons.

140
00:10:42,186 --> 00:10:44,495
Well, when you're looking at your future...

141
00:10:44,689 --> 00:10:47,249
it doesn't hurt
to find closure about the past.

142
00:10:49,777 --> 00:10:53,611
Susan, every man dreams he'll meet
a woman he can give the world to.

143
00:10:55,408 --> 00:10:57,797
In my case, it's not just a metaphor.

144
00:11:02,790 --> 00:11:05,020
<i>Opening viewing station shield. </i>

145
00:11:35,156 --> 00:11:36,589
That can't be right.

146
00:11:37,784 --> 00:11:42,300
<i>Event threshold</i>
<i>in T-minus 9 minutes, 47 seconds. </i>

147
00:11:42,747 --> 00:11:45,341
That's impossible.
It should be seven hours.

148
00:11:50,380 --> 00:11:52,291
We've been together two years now.

149
00:11:52,465 --> 00:11:56,060
It's been a good two years, Victor.
The company's accomplished so much.

150
00:11:56,302 --> 00:11:58,258
Right, of course, the company.

151
00:12:00,098 --> 00:12:03,488
But, you see, I've come to realize that
all the accomplishments in the world...

152
00:12:03,726 --> 00:12:05,682
mean nothing without someone
to share them with.

153
00:12:05,853 --> 00:12:09,607
I've lived my life
unafraid of taking big steps.

154
00:12:10,441 --> 00:12:12,955
Now it's time to take the biggest step
of all.

155
00:12:13,152 --> 00:12:17,509
- Victor.
- Lf it helps, think of this as a promotion.

156
00:12:18,533 --> 00:12:21,001
- Victor, I...
- I have four words.

157
00:12:22,620 --> 00:12:25,578
Four little words that can change
our lives forever.

158
00:12:25,790 --> 00:12:27,701
The cloud is accelerating.

159
00:12:27,875 --> 00:12:30,548
We've got minutes until it hits, not hours.

160
00:12:31,045 --> 00:12:33,115
Victor, that storm is deadly.
We need to abort.

161
00:12:33,297 --> 00:12:36,812
Get a grip, Reed. We didn't come all this
way to lose our nerve at the first glitch.

162
00:12:37,051 --> 00:12:38,086
Just close the shields.

163
00:12:38,219 --> 00:12:40,574
- Ben is still out there.
- So reel him in.

164
00:12:40,763 --> 00:12:44,233
But we came here to do a job,
so let's do it quickly.

165
00:12:45,435 --> 00:12:48,586
Victor, Reed's right.
We have less than six minutes!

166
00:12:51,566 --> 00:12:54,239
- Ben, you need to get inside now.
- What's going on?

167
00:12:54,444 --> 00:12:56,719
<i>I ain't done</i>
<i>arranging your flowers yet, egghead. </i>

168
00:12:56,904 --> 00:12:58,337
<i>Ben, turn around!</i>

169
00:13:08,082 --> 00:13:09,401
<i>Guys, I'm not gonna make it. </i>

170
00:13:09,542 --> 00:13:11,533
Ben, you gotta jump. It's the only way!

171
00:13:16,924 --> 00:13:18,721
- What are you doing?
- Closing the shields.

172
00:13:18,885 --> 00:13:21,274
- You can't just leave them out there.
- Watch me.

173
00:13:22,972 --> 00:13:26,123
- You can't help them any more than I can.
- I can try.

174
00:13:41,908 --> 00:13:43,102
Come on, Ben, you got it!

175
00:13:46,454 --> 00:13:48,888
Okay, Johnny,
get ready to close the portal.

176
00:14:43,136 --> 00:14:45,047
Wake up. Ben.

177
00:14:46,681 --> 00:14:49,036
Rise and shine, big boy. How you feeling?

178
00:14:49,809 --> 00:14:51,037
Where am I?

179
00:14:51,185 --> 00:14:54,416
Back on Earth. We're in quarantine.
Victor's medical facility.

180
00:14:54,647 --> 00:14:56,160
Reed? Sue?

181
00:14:56,315 --> 00:14:58,875
They're fine. Everybody else is fine.

182
00:15:00,737 --> 00:15:02,170
What's wrong with me?

183
00:15:03,823 --> 00:15:06,656
I swear to you, Ben. They've done
everything humanly possible.

184
00:15:06,868 --> 00:15:08,779
The best plastic surgeons
in the world are here, Ben.

185
00:15:08,953 --> 00:15:09,942
You had the best.

186
00:15:10,079 --> 00:15:13,196
- Give me that mirror.
- I don't know if that's a good idea.

187
00:15:13,416 --> 00:15:16,533
- They said the shock alone...
- I said give me that goddamn mirror!

188
00:15:16,753 --> 00:15:19,631
Okay, Ben, just be strong.

189
00:15:24,344 --> 00:15:27,973
Unfortunately, the doctors
just couldn't do anything to fix your face.

190
00:15:33,936 --> 00:15:34,971
- Hi.
- Hey.

191
00:15:35,104 --> 00:15:37,982
Nice do. I'm liking the grandpa look.

192
00:15:38,858 --> 00:15:39,927
What?

193
00:15:58,169 --> 00:16:01,286
- How's she doing?
- Stable and her vitals are strong.

194
00:16:01,798 --> 00:16:04,266
Blood panels show no irradiation. Good.

195
00:16:05,093 --> 00:16:08,324
- You'll step up this protocol every...
- Every four hours, yes.

196
00:16:08,554 --> 00:16:10,146
We know what we're doing.

197
00:16:10,306 --> 00:16:12,661
Another day of observation
and you're all clear.

198
00:16:12,850 --> 00:16:15,569
Excuse me.
More flowers from Mr. Von Doom.

199
00:16:19,065 --> 00:16:20,862
She's allergic to orchids.

200
00:16:21,025 --> 00:16:23,858
Put the sunflowers by her bed,
they're her favorites.

201
00:16:41,921 --> 00:16:43,593
Well, Victor...

202
00:16:44,048 --> 00:16:46,118
the bank would like to congratulate you...

203
00:16:46,300 --> 00:16:48,734
on the fastest freefall
since the Depression.

204
00:16:48,928 --> 00:16:50,441
We can't even give your stock away.

205
00:16:50,596 --> 00:16:52,109
Ned, you know I can turn this around.

206
00:16:52,265 --> 00:16:55,143
Well, you're going to have to, Victor,
or we pull out.

207
00:16:57,770 --> 00:16:59,089
You have a week.

208
00:16:59,230 --> 00:17:01,380
You're enjoying this, aren't you, Ned?

209
00:17:05,611 --> 00:17:06,885
One week.

210
00:17:19,459 --> 00:17:21,290
Where do we think we're going?

211
00:17:21,461 --> 00:17:22,655
I don't know if we've noticed...

212
00:17:22,795 --> 00:17:25,673
but the sickest runs this side of the Alps
are right outside that window.

213
00:17:25,882 --> 00:17:28,316
Yeah, I've noticed,
but there are rules here.

214
00:17:28,509 --> 00:17:30,739
- You can't leave until we...
- Until we've finish the tests.

215
00:17:30,928 --> 00:17:35,126
I know, I've never been good with rules.
You let me know how those come out.

216
00:17:35,933 --> 00:17:39,482
- Do you wanna help me with this zipper?
- You know, this is not a ski resort.

217
00:17:39,729 --> 00:17:42,482
Not yet. Luckily, Grandma still sends
care packages, though.

218
00:17:42,690 --> 00:17:45,921
You know, it's amazing, for an 80-year-old
woman, you'd be surprised...

219
00:17:46,152 --> 00:17:49,189
- You are trouble.
- Trouble is my middle name.

220
00:17:49,405 --> 00:17:50,474
You're hot!

221
00:17:50,615 --> 00:17:52,731
Why, thank you. So are you.
And I'm not afraid to cry.

222
00:17:52,909 --> 00:17:54,342
No, I mean, you feel a little feverish.

223
00:17:54,494 --> 00:17:57,247
Well, I've never felt better in my life.
My God, you smell good.

224
00:17:57,455 --> 00:17:59,411
Listen, when do you get off work?

225
00:17:59,666 --> 00:18:01,258
- 4:00, but I...
- Tell you what.

226
00:18:01,417 --> 00:18:04,250
You meet me at 4:01
at the top of the mountain.

227
00:18:05,088 --> 00:18:08,524
That'll give you a minute to freshen up.
This is yours, that's mine.

228
00:18:09,425 --> 00:18:10,574
Nurses!

229
00:18:16,349 --> 00:18:17,987
How long was I out?

230
00:18:18,351 --> 00:18:19,340
Hey.

231
00:18:19,477 --> 00:18:22,150
Three days. Man, I was worried about you.

232
00:18:22,522 --> 00:18:24,592
- How are you feeling?
- Solid.

233
00:18:26,484 --> 00:18:28,600
- That was a close one, though, huh?
- Yeah.

234
00:18:28,778 --> 00:18:31,087
- What was that about?
- I don't know.

235
00:18:32,490 --> 00:18:34,128
I really don't know.

236
00:18:34,283 --> 00:18:37,878
I've been going over the figures
again and again and they all add up.

237
00:18:39,080 --> 00:18:40,957
I just don't understand.
Maybe I should have aborted...

